This is a very important distinction to understand because if one part of your application "hogs" the pool with a massive task, it can slow down every other parallel stream running in that same program.
1. The Common ForkJoinPool
When you call .parallelStream(), your lambdas are sent to the Common ForkJoinPool.
 * Size: By default, this pool has a number of threads equal to the number of logical processors on your machine minus one (N-1).
 * Reasoning: If you have an 8-core CPU, the pool creates 7 threads. The 8th thread is the "main" thread that initiated the stream, ensuring all cores stay busy.
2. Can you create multiple pools?
Yes, but it's a bit of a "hack." If you have a specific task that is very slow (like a web request) and you don't want it to block your high-speed math calculations in the common pool, you can wrap your parallel stream inside a custom ForkJoinPool.
// Create a private kitchen (pool) with 4 threads
ForkJoinPool customPool = new ForkJoinPool(4);

try {
    customPool.submit(() -> 
        largeDataset.parallelStream()
            .forEach(data -> process(data)) // Runs in customPool, NOT the common pool
    ).get();
} finally {
    customPool.shutdown();
}

3. The "Worker Thread" Lifecycle
It is helpful to visualize how the threads handle your lambdas. Instead of creating a new thread for every single item in your list (which would crash your computer), the pool uses Work-Stealing:
 * Split: The list is broken into chunks.
 * Assign: Each thread in the pool gets a "todo list" of chunks.
 * Steal: If Thread A finishes its list early, it "steals" a chunk from the back of Thread B's list to keep the CPU 100% utilized.
Comparison: Common vs. Custom Pool
| Feature | Common Pool (Default) | Custom Pool |
|---|---|---|
| Creation | Automatic | Manual (new ForkJoinPool()) |
| Thread Count | Fixed (CPUs - 1) | Configurable |
| Best For | Fast, CPU-bound tasks | Slow, I/O-bound, or isolated tasks |
| Risk | Can be "polluted" by slow tasks | Higher memory overhead |
Why this matters
If you are building a web server (like a Spring Boot app) and you use .parallelStream() inside your API controllers, remember that every single user request will be fighting for the same small set of threads in that common pool. One heavy request could potentially make the entire server feel sluggish!
