In this example, I've added a thread name printout so you can actually see that the custom pool threads (usually named something like ForkJoinPool-1-worker-X) are the ones doing the heavy lifting, rather than the default common pool.
Full Java Example: Custom ForkJoinPool
This code creates a custom pool of 4 threads to process a list of numbers.
import java.util.List;
import java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinPool;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;
import java.util.stream.IntStream;

public class ParallelCustomPool {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // 1. Create a large dataset
        List<Integer> dataset = IntStream.rangeClosed(1, 10)
                                         .boxed()
                                         .collect(Collectors.toList());

        // 2. Define a custom pool with a specific number of threads
        int parallelism = 4;
        ForkJoinPool customPool = new ForkJoinPool(parallelism);

        try {
            System.out.println("Starting parallel processing in custom pool...");

            // 3. Submit the parallel stream task to the custom pool
            customPool.submit(() -> 
                dataset.parallelStream().forEach(data -> {
                    processTask(data);
                })
            ).get(); // .get() waits for the entire stream to finish

        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        } finally {
            // 4. Always shut down your custom pool to prevent memory leaks
            customPool.shutdown();
            System.out.println("Custom pool shut down.");
        }
    }

    private static void processTask(Integer data) {
        String threadName = Thread.currentThread().getName();
        System.out.println("Processing value " + data + " on thread: " + threadName);
        
        try {
            // Simulate a time-consuming task (e.g., database call or complex math)
            Thread.sleep(100); 
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        }
    }
}

What’s happening in this code?
 * IntStream.rangeClosed: This is a quick way to generate a list of numbers from 1 to 10.
 * customPool.submit(...): This is the "magic" part. When you call a parallelStream inside a task submitted to a specific ForkJoinPool, the stream is smart enough to use that pool instead of the system default.
 * .get(): This is a blocking call. Because submit is asynchronous (it returns a Future), we use .get() to tell the main thread: "Wait here until the parallel work is totally done."
 * processTask: I added a Thread.sleep here. Without it, the code would run so fast you wouldn't see the parallel threads actually working together!
